				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$P_i = \frac{{e^{ - \left( {G_i/k_{\rm B}T} \right)}}}{{\mathop {\sum }\nolimits_j^N e^{ - \left( {G_j/k_{\rm B}T} \right)}}}$$\end{document}Pi=e-Gi∕kBT∑jNe-Gj∕kBTwhere N is the total number of structures classified as knotted or unknotted, i is the ith conformation, G
i is the Rosetta energy obtained for conformation i, k
B is the Boltzmann constant, and T is the absolute temperature. The temperature term k
B
T was set to 1 Rosetta Energy Unit (REU). 1 REU corresponds to about 0.57 kcal mol−1 based on comparative studies between experimentally determined ΔΔGs and the REU predicted by Rosetta upon punctual mutations of proteins54. The free energy difference between knotted and unknotted structures (ΔG
N = G
unknotted-G
knotted) was estimated by ΔG
N = −RT ln(P
unknotted)/(P
knotted), where R is the ideal gas constant.

The molecular extension change (Δx
exp) and the folding (F
R) and unfolding (F
U) forces of the stretched proteins was determined for each force–extension curve. In order to calculate the experimental contour length (L
c exp) the Δx
exp data were compared with the molecular extension change predicted by the WLC model (Δx
theoretical) for each observed force. To calculate Δx
theoretical values, the theoretical contour length (L
c theoretical) expected for the full Arc-L1-Arc (42 nm, 120 residues × 0.35 nm per aa) or pARC (36.05 nm, 103 residues × 0.35 nm per aa) and a persistence length of 0.65 nm were used as parameters for the WLC model. In this way, a Δx
theoretical value was determined for each force. The L
c exp distribution was calculated as follows:\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
